					<description><![CDATA[<p>TensorWave has successfully closed a $350 million Series B funding round. The investment, which values the three-year-old startup at $1.55 billion, signals a major market bet on AMD-powered infrastructure as</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/tensorwave-raises-350m-to-expand-ai-infrastructure/" data-wpel-link="internal">TensorWave Raises $350M to Expand AI Infrastructure</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://tensorwave.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">TensorWave </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has successfully closed a $350 million Series B </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/minerva-raises-20m-to-transform-marketing-technology/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round. The investment, which values the three-year-old startup at $1.55 billion, signals a major market bet on AMD-powered infrastructure as a viable alternative for the world’s most demanding AI workloads.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The round was co-led by AMD Ventures and the specialised investment firm Magnetar Capital. The deal is structurally significant as it sees AMD, the primary chip supplier for TensorWave, using its own balance sheet to aggressively fund a major customer, mirroring a strategic playbook long utilised by Nvidia to secure market share for its own accelerators.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Building the Nvidia-Free Cloud</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded in 2023 by Darrick Horton (CEO) and Jeff Tatarchuk, TensorWave has distinguished itself by being one of the first neocloud providers to reject Nvidia’s H100 and Blackwell architectures entirely. Instead, the company has hitched its wagon to AMD’s Instinct accelerators and the open-source ROCm software stack.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_202745" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202745" class="size-large wp-image-202745" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/AI-5-1024x576.jpg" alt="AI" width="1024" height="576" /><p id="caption-attachment-202745" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400"><br />
</span><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;We were created to restore competition to the market,&#8221; CEO Darrick Horton said in a statement following the raise. &#8220;The AI industry cannot scale on a single-vendor obstacle. By building an optimised, liquid-cooled cloud specifically for AMD hardware, we are giving developers the performance they need without the multi-month wait times typical of Nvidia-based clusters.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The capital injection arrives as TensorWave scales its operational footprint. The company has already deployed what it describes as the world&#8217;s largest liquid-cooled AMD GPU training cluster, featuring approximately 8,000 AMD Instinct MI325X accelerators.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/minerva-raises-20m-to-transform-marketing-technology/?amp=1" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Minerva Raises $20M to Transform Marketing Technology</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Infrastructure at Gigawatt Scale</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The $350 million will be used primarily to purchase more silicon and secure the massive power capacity required for the next generation of LLM (Large Language Model) training. TensorWave recently entered a multi-phase capacity agreement with TECfusions to target a staggering one gigawatt of power across its data centre roadmap.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">While the initial deployments in 2025 and early 2026 are focused on the 10-to-20 megawatt range, the long-term vision is to provide a sovereign AI cloud that can support the training of models with trillions of parameters. By utilising liquid-cooling technology, TensorWave states it can operate these high-density AMD chips at higher sustained clock speeds while maintaining a lower PUE than an air-cooled data centre.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Strategic Implications for the Chip Wars</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">For AMD, the investment in TensorWave is a tactical necessity. While AMD’s hardware is widely considered the most potent competitor to Nvidia on paper, the lack of a mature cloud ecosystem has hindered its adoption. By backing TensorWave, AMD ensures there is a high-profile, highly optimised environment where AI researchers can experience the Instinct platform at scale.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The raise also highlights the &#8220;flight to quality&#8221; in AI infrastructure funding. While many general-purpose cloud startups have struggled to find a footing, TensorWave’s revenue has grown significantly, with reports suggesting the firm’s valuation has nearly quadrupled from roughly $400 million just one year ago.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/tensorwave-raises-350m-to-expand-ai-infrastructure/" data-wpel-link="internal">TensorWave Raises $350M to Expand AI Infrastructure</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
